<TEXT>
a guyanese immigrant convicted of killing his 
girlfriend and four members of her family in a jealous rage lost 
appeals tuesday in state and federal courts in his lastminute bid 
to avoid the electric chair 
the louisiana supreme court and then us district judge peter 
beer refused to put off the execution of leslie lowenfield 34 
which is set for early wednesday 
lowenfields attorneys then went to the 5th us circuit court 
of appeals with the plea that he is mentally ill and therefore 
unable to understand the death penalty 
at the louisiana state penitentiary warden hilton butler said 
lowenfield was still hoping for a fifth delay of as many execution 
dates 
butler said lowenfield spurned the condemneds customary last 
meal and spent the evening with dale brown the head basketball 
coach from louisiana state university 
brown widely recognized as a motivational speaker had been 
corresponding with lowenfield since he took the lsu team on a tour 
of angolas death row in 1984 butler said 
a catholic priest and nun also were with lowenfield the warden 
said 
lowenfield a welder from guyana who came to the united states 
in 1981 on a work permit was convicted in 1984 in the august 1982 
slayings of his estranged girlfriend who was a jefferson parish 
sheriffs deputy and four others 
the case has already been appealed unsuccessfully to both the 
states highest court and the us supreme court lawyers based 
their latest appeal on a recent psychological study that found the 
prisoner to be a paranoid schizophrenic 
there is a serious question about leslies competency to be 
executed due to his mental illness said judith menadue attorney 
for the louisiana capital defense project 
she said the us supreme court has ruled that people who cannot 
understand what it means to be executed may not be put to death 
before the trial lowenfield was found competent and he refused 
to allow his lawyers to use insanity as a defense insisting 
instead that he was in florida at the time the family was killed 
but no witnesses backed up his story of being out of state 
the denial of the stay was issued without further comment from 
the state supreme court majority but the one member who backed the 
appeal issued a brief dissent 
the clinical psychologist who spent five hours with the 
defendant concluded lowenfield indicated that he is currently 
unable to understand the death penalty justice john a dixon 
wrote 
he noted that criminal law calls for halting prosecution when 
there are reasonable grounds to doubt a defendants sanity and for 
going ahead after that only when the defendant is found to have the 
mental capacity to do so 
prosecutors said lowenfield barged into his girlfriends house 
in marrero a new orleans suburb and shot everybody there 
the victims were the girlfriend sheila thomas 27 her 
daughter shantel osborne 4 her stepfather owen griffin 45 her 
mother myrtle griffin 44 and the little girls father carl 
osborne 33 
the prosecution said lowenfield was jealous of miss thomas they 
said the couple had lived together in a stormy relationship until 
earlier in the summer of 1982 when he set the house on fire and she 
moved out 
investigators found a notebook full of obscenities and threats 
in one place he wrote she have to go to the wormes she took all 
i work for then leave to go and be with carl but i just cannot take 
it eany more 
lowenfield was arrested two months later in new york 
parts of the evidence against him were letters he wrote miss 
thomas relatives while he was jailed in new york one said osborne 
had grabbed the child as a shield and lowenfield had shot both of 
them 
on trial lowenfield insisted on an alibi defense saying he was 
in jacksonville fla looking for work at the time of the murders 
after a separate trial to determine the penalty jurors came 
back three times saying they could not decide whether he should 
die prodded on by the judge they decided on the fourth try to 
condemn him to death 
</TEXT>
