<TEXT>
soybean market prices are averaging the most 
in three years because of greater world demand and a tightening of 
available supplies an agriculture department analysis shows 
drought has damaged brazils soybean crop and the european 
economic community has increased its demand for the oilseed the 
departments economic research service said monday that has helped 
whittle down us soybean stockpiles and boost prices 
the supplyanddemand report said soybean prices now could 
average in the range of 550 to 580 per bushel in the marketing 
year that began last sept 1 up from 535 to 575 forecast in 
march prices averaged 478 per bushel in the 198687 season 
according to usda records that would be the most since soybeans 
averaged 584 per bushel in 198485 they were 783 in the 
198384 marketing year 
soybean exports were forecast at 785 million bushels up from 
760 million indicated last month and the 757 million bushels 
shipped in 198687 
wheat exports also have improved due mainly to subsidized sales 
to the soviet union under the departments export enhancement 
program or eep 
in all exports in the wheat marketing year that runs through 
may 31 are estimated at 16 billion bushels a 60 percent increase 
from 1 billion bushels shipped in 198687 average market prices 
for this season were put at 255 per bushel up from 242 last 
year 
corn exports also are up rising to an estimated 17 billion 
bushels in the corn marketing year that began last sept 1 
compared with 15 billion bushels in 198687 
market prices of corn were forecast to average 165 to 185 
per bushel this season up from 150 in 198687 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
agriculture department scientists are looking 
at the neem tree of asia and africa as a possible source of 
material to prevent the formation of aflatoxin a food toxin that 
occurs in nature 
aflatoxin can be produced by fungi that forms on some farm crops 
under certain conditions including corn and oilseeds laboratory 
tests with animals have shown that aflatoxin is among the most 
powerful cancercausing agents known and usda has called it a 
potential hazard to humans 
deepak bhatnagar said in a report released here that as a child 
in india his parents used to put leaves of the neem tree inside 
containers of wheat to keep insects from the grain now as a usda 
scientist he has found that the leaves may also block fungi from 
producing aflatoxin 
in tests at the departments agricultural research service 
center in new orleans la bhatnagar made solutions containing 
neem leaves he found that the solutions didnt kill the fungi but 
did block more than 98 percent of the aflatoxin they normally would 
have produced 
the fungi that produce the toxin are aspergillus flavus and a 
parasiticus 
bhatnagar said the results were promising but preliminary 
and that greenhouse studies with cotton are now being planned 
the ornamental neem is also known as margosa and nim more than 
80 insect pests including mexican bean beetles colorado potato 
beetles tobacco budworms and carpet beetles are repelled by neem 
extracts 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
spice imports totaled about 439 million last 
year up 12 percent from 1986 says the agriculture department 
the rise was due mainly to larger imports of vanilla beans 
white pepper nutmeg and mace cassia cumin anise capsicum 
peppers laurel and thyme the departments foreign agricultural 
service reported monday higher prices of many of the items also 
were a factor 
saffron prices have soared in recent months reflecting a 
short spanish crop the report said 
also it added cesium contamination from the soviet unions 
nuclear mishap at chernobyl two years ago has kept supplies tight 
and prices firm for several mediterraneanarea herbs such as 
oregano laurel rosemary and sage 
</TEXT>
