<TEXT>
americans are more willing than their 
representatives in congress to consider changes in the social 
security system but no single option for cutting costs has broad 
public support according to a survey 
the public also strongly favors pulling us troops out of 
europe as a way to reduce the federal budget deficit according to 
the survey by the league of concerned americans a charlotte 
ncbased nonprofit group 
the league commissioned the nationwide poll as part of a project 
called americas budget an effort to determine national 
spending priorities from a nonwashington perspective it planned 
to release a suggested budget today 
a lot of things that are perceptually true in washington 
are not that way across the country said scott rasmussen 
founder of the league 
for example an informal congressional survey showed 80 percent 
of the members favored leaving the social security system 
untouched only 34 percent favored that option in the nationwide 
poll 
however people differed over what changes should be made the 
poll showed 
from a list of options 21 percent favored making the system 
voluntary and 25 percent supported raising the retirement age to 
allow a drop in the social security tax only 6 percent favored 
cutting costofliving adjustments for retirees the most 
frequently mentioned option when washington considers cutbacks 
congress has been holding hearings this year on what lawmakers 
call burden sharing forcing us allies to take on more of 
the cost of defending against the soviet bloc 
the informal survey of congress showed only 12 percent said they 
would favor gradually withdrawing a substantial portion of us 
troops from western europe over the next 20 years however more 
than three out of four citizens polled supported the idea 
the poll was conducted for the league by marketwise inc the 
random sample of 519 respondents has a margin of error of 43 
percentage points 
despite the 1983 changes in the social security which included 
raising taxes to build up big surpluses over the next few years 
more than a fourth of the people polled still doubt whether their 
benefits will be there when they retire according to the survey 
i think there is a real temptation to spend the money if 
there are surpluses said rasmussen 
sen lawton chiles dfla chairman of the senate budget 
committee said monday he would propose a resolution to put 
congress on record opposing the current accounting system which 
allows social security surpluses to hide the true size of the 
governments operating deficit 
rasmussen a business entrepreneur who with his father founded 
the espn sports network in 1978 said he hoped the league would 
help prod the politicians to keep working toward a balanced budget 
the results were being presented to the new national commission on 
the deficit which will make recommendations for the next president 
and congress on ways to cut red ink he said 
</TEXT>
