<DOCNO> AP880412-0072 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
describing an ache may be easy to the sufferer 
but to pain researchers the feeling of hurt is complex almost 
beyond description 
researchers at a fourday international pain measurement 
conference that began monday are trying to develop a unified theory 
for the study of pain the conference is sponsored by the 
university of washington and funded by a grant from the national 
institutes of health 
one in three people in america suffers from chronic pain and 
millions are routinely incapacitated by it but medical science 
often can do little to to prevent or effectively treat recurrent 
pain because patients are suffering from something that cant be 
seen felt or observed by someone else 
the subjective and intangible nature of pain frustrates many 
people involved in its research 
the problem with the meaning of the word pain has been around 
since aristotle said dr john d loeser a neurosurgeon and 
director of the universitys multidisciplinary pain center 
how do you go about measuring pain loeser asks were not 
very far along in the clinical setting its too complex a 
phenomenon 
only within about the last two decades has the problem of pain 
gained serious attention in medical research in large part because 
of the pioneering efforts of dr john bonica chairman emeritus of 
the schools department of anesthesiology bonicas work on the 
management of pain which emphasizes a comprehensive approach 
rather than hitandmiss drug therapies paved the way for the 
serious study of pain 
everybody measures pain in a different way said c richard 
chapman a psychopharmacologist in pain research at the university 
and the independent fred hutchinson cancer research center 
we dont at present have a theory a single theory that 
everyone agrees upon said chapman 
pain measurement research generally relies on laboratory tests 
of animals lab tests on humans or studies of patient care each 
with its own accepted methods for measuring and defining pain none 
completely translates into an acceptable method for the other 
chapman said pain often is taken seriously by medical 
professionals only when tissue damage can be identified although a 
lot of chronic pain apparently exists without any identifiable 
tissue damage 
some researchers try to measure this kind of pain by analyzing 
behavior or looking at brain waves and other electrical signals 
those dealing with humans ask the sufferer to describe the hurt 
but how can you tell if an infant who cant yet speak is 
experiencing pain asked loeser 
university of washington researchers expect a good deal of 
argument and contention at the conference in fact they 
deliberately scheduled scientists with opposing views to speak in 
succession about 60 researchers are expected to attend 
its my belief that we can bring this all together if we can 
find a uniform theory for pain said chapman when we have 
reached it our power to solve the perplexities of pain 
scientifically and to control the human and animal suffering that 
it causes will be greatly increased 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

