<TEXT>
chinas legislature approved a new cabinet today 
that includes younger members more closely tied to economic reforms 
of senior leader deng xiaoping and communist party general 
secretary zhao ziyang 
the 2859 delegates of the national peoples congress also 
passed constitutional amendments sanctioning private businesses and 
the right to transfer use of land 
delegates confirmed 41 ministerial posts named three vice 
premiers and appointed nine as state councilors to the state 
council or cabinet 
they also trimmed the council as part of government efforts to 
become more efficient eliminating posts for two vice premiers two 
state councilors and four ministers 
qian qichen 60 who has been vice foreign minister in charge of 
relations with the soviet union succeeded wu xueqian as foreign 
minister while gen qin jiwei 74 a member of the politburo and 
head of the beijing military region took over the defense ministry 
from ailing zhang aiping 78 
the three vice premiers who will serve under premier li peng are 
outgoing foreign minister wu 67 state planning commission 
minister yao yilin 71 and tian jiyun 59 yao and tian previously 
served as vice premiers 
ten of the 41 ministers are new as are seven of the nine state 
councilors the average age of the premier vice premiers and nine 
councilors dropped from 67 to 61 
the state councilors include people closely identified with 
zhaos economic reforms and policy of opening to the outside world 
such as new state education commission minister li tieying and 
beijing mayor chen xitong and chen junsheng who also retained his 
post of secretary general of the state council 
one constitutional amendment guarantees the rights and interests 
of the 215 million chinese now working in 137 million private 
businesses private entrepreneurs operating small food and 
clothing stalls and restaurants now account for almost 13 percent 
of the nations total retail sales 
the other amendment also tied to chinas policy of giving 
greater flexibility to its economy states that the right to the 
use of land may be transferred according to law 
china has experimented with transfer of landuse rights as part 
of efforts to provide land to more ambitious farmers and accelerate 
urban development 
chinas foreign policy is not expected to change under qian a 
career diplomat who spent 10 years in the soviet union and has 
headed chinasoviet normalization talks since 1982 qian who also 
has been chinas spokesman on disarmament issues speaks english 
and russian 
under wu foreign minister since november 1982 china has 
maintained a course of neutrality in superpower disputes increased 
economic and political ties with the west eased tensions with 
moscow and championed third world causes 
qin jiwei a close confidante of deng xiaoping who served under 
deng in the wars against japan and the nationalists is expected to 
lead efforts to restore the defense ministrys authority over the 
peoples liberation army 
among other major appointments premier li took over the state 
commission for restructuring the economy which is responsible for 
setting guidelines for chinas marketoriented reforms vice 
premier yao yilin was confirmed as head of the state planning 
commission newly created out of two commissions 
li and yao are both regarded as more cautious than party head 
zhao toward reforms designed to substitute central planning with 
marketdetermined production their leadership over the two key 
economic commissions could slow down the pace of new reform 
initiatives in coming years 
li senmao 58 was named railways minister to succeed ding 
guangen who was forced to resign last month following a string of 
fatal accidents li has been vice minister since 1982 
li guixian a soviettrained engineer who was party chief in 
anhui province was named governor of the peoples bank of china 
succeeding chen muhua one of the highestranking women in the 
government 
</TEXT>
