<DOCNO> AP880412-0144 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
makers of plastic foam food containers will 
stop using ozonedestroying chemicals in their products after this 
year the first industry to give up the compounds completely their 
trade association said tuesday 
major environmental groups and the environmental protection 
agency hailed the decision by members of the foodservice amp packing 
institute as an important symbolic step in persuading others to 
find substitutes for the chlorofluorocarbon or cfc compounds 
consumers will notice little impact because the the decision 
does not mean an end to foam containers valued for their lightness 
and insulating properties things like egg cartons and the 
clamshell hamburger containers used by fastfood chains twothirds 
of those foams currently are made without cfcs 
there are about 15 companies making the food packages said 
joseph w bow president of the institute and more than a third of 
them have signed a letter pledging to give up cfcs by the end of 
the year in 30 days we should have the rest of the industry 
signed up bow said 
about 15 percent to 2 percent of cfc use in the united states 
or 15 million pounds a year goes to foam blowing agents for food 
packages though 30 percent is used in blowing agents for other 
foams such as seat cushions and insulating panels gaseous cfcs are 
released into the atmosphere during the foam manufacturing process 
and some of the compounds also remain trapped in the foam where 
they may be released into the environment later 
for environmentalists though the food packages were a visible 
symbol of the threat to the earths protective ozone layer and 
they already had persuaded some fast food chains and the senate 
restaurant in washington not to use cfcderived containers 
ozone at high altitudes protects the earth from cancercausing 
ultraviolet rays of the sun but can be destroyed by chlorine 
liberated from the breakup of cfc compounds at those altitudes 
last month the national aeronautics and space administration 
reported that cfcs appear to have been responsible for an average 
23 percent decline in the ozone shield at northern hemisphere 
midlatitudes from 1969 to 1986 
a treaty signed by 31 nations last fall requires a 50 percent 
cut in cfc production by 1998 
most of the replacement for cfcs in foam packages is expected to 
be a related compound hcfc22 which has only 5 percent of the 
ozonedestroying ability of the chemicals being given up 
the natural resources defense council the environmental defense 
fund and friends of the earth agreed to work with the packing 
institute in finding an eventual replacement for hcfc22 
all three groups praised the industry and epa administrator lee 
m thomas issued a statement praising the welcome contribution 
of less cfc use as a model of cooperation between industry and 
the environmental community 
the environmental defense fund said the announcement was even 
more significant than the du pont cos announcement last month 
that it wanted to end cfc production because du pont did not commit 
itself to a deadline the way the institute did 
it is our intention to go to other sectors of the economy 
and say these guys did it so can you said david doniger 
attorney for the natural resources defense council 
current noncfc blowing agents mostly volatile hydrocarbons 
like pentane pose environmental threats of their own since these 
compounds help form ozone at low altitudes where it is a pollutant 
the substitute material costs 25 percent to 50 percent more than 
the compounds it replaces but lasts longer so costs will be 
increased little if at all bow said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

