<TEXT>
chinese leaders on tuesday elected a new cabinet 
in a vote that indicates a general support for deng xiaopings 
economic reforms although several conservatives received key posts 
qian qichen 60 a career diplomat who has been chinas chief 
negotiator with the soviet union was elected as minister of 
foreign affairs succeeding wu xueqian 67 
gen qin jiwei 74 a member of the communist party politburo 
and commander of the beijing military region took over the defense 
ministry from ailing zhang aiping 78 
continuing an unprecedented movement started at the beginning of 
congress delegates at the national peoples congress actually 
voted against some of the cabinet candidates 
in congresses past all candidates were elected unanimously 
the congress which is chinas legislature also passed two 
amendments to the constitution one guarantees the rights of 
private businessmen while the other recognizes the transfer of 
landuse rights opening the way for the leasing of property 
in voting by 2859 delegates the congress approved three vice 
premiers nine state councillors and 41 ministers for the state 
council or cabinet the stress was on continuity with the large 
majority of ministers either keeping their jobs or turning them 
over to people within their organizations 
the state council is headed by li peng 59 who was formally 
endorsed as premier earlier in the congress annual session 
named as vice premiers were yao yilin and tian jiyun both 
returnees and the outgoing foreign minister wu 
the delegates were not given a choice in who they could pick for 
each office although they could oppose the candidate or abstain 
from voting 
the one surprise was the election of li guixian a 
soviettrained engineer and party boss in anhui province to be 
governor of the peoples bank of china the central bank 
li with no known financial background will be responsible for 
the major task of reforming chinas inflexible banking system to 
allow interest rates to replace central planning in the management 
of the bank 
according to new evening post a hong kong daily he received 404 
opposing votes and 29 abstentions more than any other candidate 
as head of the defense ministry qin one of dengs confidantes 
is expected to carry out dengs plan to mold the defense ministry 
into a more powerful body 
the ministry is now the weak sister to party and state military 
commissions both headed by deng 
qian the new foreign minister is expected to follow closely 
the policies laid down by wu foreign minister since 1982 
china in that period has steadily expanded economic and 
political ties with the west while gradually easing tensions with 
the soviet union 
the official news agency xinhua described the new government as 
a group of technocrats who are younger in age pragmatic and 
enthusiastic in the reform 
it said the average age of the cabinet dipped from 62 to 59 and 
that all but five members are college graduates 
premier li a soviettrained engineer who is considered 
conservative when compared to communist party leader zhao ziyang 
took over the state commission for restructuring the economy 
senior vice premier yao who also wants to slow the pace of 
reform was named head of the new state planning commission 
one constitutional amendment guarantees the rights and interests 
of the 215 million chinese now engaged in 137 million private 
businesses private entrepreneurs operating small food and 
clothing stalls and restaurants now account for almost 13 percent 
of the nations total retail sales 
the other amendment also tied to chinas policy of giving 
greater flexibility to its economy states that the right to the 
use of land may be transferred according to law 
china has experimented with transfer of landuse rights as part 
of efforts to provide land to more ambitious farmers and accelerate 
urban development 
the congress which closes wednesday has been hailed as the 
most democratic in history with delegates encouraged to speak out 
on such issues as inflation and faltering agricultural production 
</TEXT>
