the bureau of land management said tuesday it 
is going to decide whether recent allegations of cruelty to animals 
should mean an end to its practice of giving away large numbers of 
wild horses 
were putting the largescale adoptions under an intensive 
review blm spokesman tim locke said but he declined to confirm 
a report that the nofee largeherd adoption program had been 
suspended 
since the mid1970s the bureau has offered for adoption the 
wild horses taken in its roundups from the western range on payment 
of 125 
use of the term adoption is really a marketing tool since 
after a year the bureau gives the foster parent title to the 
horse 
since 1984 the bureau has waived the fee for people willing to 
take 100 animals or more 
locke said the review was prompted by recent allegations of 
abuse including one at sheyenne nd where earlier this month 
bureau officials reclaimed what was left of a herd of 400 horses on 
a ranch there 
fortytwo horses were missing and 87 had died mostly of 
dehydration or starvation 
the grand forks nd herald last week quoted john boyles head 
of the bureaus wild horse and burro division as saying were 
not approving any more than those already approved 
both boyles and robert burford director of the bureau were 
traveling tuesday and unavailable for comment locke would say 
only the instruction memo has not been issued largescale 
adoptions are still in our regs 
locke said burford would take up the question when he returns 
last year the bureau transferred 8600 horses to private 
caretakers in largeherd nofee adoptions these are generally 
horses that no one has taken in individual adoptions and 
frequently undesirable because older horses are more difficult to 
break 
about 5000 horses a year are adopted by individuals 
the bureau has to round up horses to keep them from eating so 
much forage that cattle cannot graze on the range it previously 
killed the surplus animals but it abandoned that practice in 1982 
following protests by animal rights groups 
