verify an arms control pact signed at the summit last december a 
us spokesman said 
the dozen or so soviets arrived at dulles international airport 
on an aeroflot flight from moscow and were to open talks wedneday 
with an american team headed by brig gen roland lajoie said the 
spokesman cmdr ken pease 
the soviet team is headed by gen vladimir medvedev who helped 
negotiate the intermediaterange nuclear forces treaty under which 
the superpowers are to destroy nucleartipped missiles with ranges 
from 300 to 3000 miles 
lajoie heads the onsite inspection agency created shortly 
after president reagan and kremlin leader mikhail s gorbachev 
signed the inf accord at the washington summit last december 
in talks scheduled to last until saturday lajoie and medvedev 
will discuss what a us official called housekeeping details 
such as living quarters for the inspectors the transportation of 
equipment and call signs that aircraft carrying the teams will use 
while in the others airspace said american officials 
the us agency will select and train an estimated 125 people to 
monitor the destruction of the soviet missiles and verify that no 
more are deployed 
thirty days after reagan and gorbachev notify each other that 
the treaty has been ratified and is in effect members of the us 
teams will visit 126 sites in the soviet union six in east 
germany and one in czechoslovakia over two months to verify data 
supplied by the soviets concerning their forces 
the soviets will visit 21 sites in the united states and western 
europe where the missiles have been made or deployed 
once those inspections are complete teams of 30 us inspectors 
will be stationed for three months at a stretch over the next 13 
years in the small city of votkinsk near the ural mountains where 
the soviets produce a longer range missile that resembles the 
ss20 one of the weapons banned under the inf pact 
the soviets will station similar teams in magna utah where the 
united states has been producing components of pershing 2 missiles 
also to be eliminated under the treaty 
</TEXT>
