<TEXT>
palestinians say a feeling they have been 
neglected by the world and other arabs tough statements from 
israel and daybyday frustrations of occupation led to the 
rebellion in the west bank and gaza strip 
the spark was a traffic accident dec 8 in which an israeli army 
truck killed four arabs near the jabaliya refugee camp in the gaza 
strip 
tensions were such that arabs saw it not as an accident but as 
revenge for the stabbing death in gaza city two days earlier of 
shlomo sakel an israeli businessman 
anger had been building among palestinians because they felt 
abandoned by arab nations and the world community the arab summit 
at amman jordan in november and the ussoviet summit in 
washington in december did not give priority to the palestinian 
issue 
it was clear to us that we had been put on the shelf said 
saeb erakat a political science professor at an najah university 
in the west bank 
the message of the uprising is that we dont wish to become 
israelis we are not a mere community or a minority living in 
greater israel we are a people and we demand our liberty and 
our right to selfdetermination 
prime minister yitzhak shamir rubbed salt in the wound by noting 
publicly that the arab summit put the iraniraq war ahead of the 
palestinian issue 
he and other rightwing leaders suggested the status quo could 
continue indefinitely and israel had a right to keep the lands it 
captured in the 1967 middle east war 
this deepened the bitterness palestinian statements became 
extreme in rejecting negotiations for a peaceful settlement 
an example of the harder line could be found in the poetry of 
mahmoud darwish an israeli arab living in paris who had favored 
israelipalestinian dialogue 
many saw his poem those who pass between fleeting words as a 
demand for all of israel not just the occupied west bank and gaza 
strip 
about the israelis it says 
o those who pass between fleeting words 
carry your names and be gone 
rid our time of your hours and be gone 
steal what you will from the blueness of the sea and the sand 
of memory 
sari nusseibeh a palestinian intellectual who advocates a 
negotiated settlement said many want all israel included in a 
palestinian state just as some israelis want all the land for the 
jewish state 
the question is whether both sides are ready to settle for 
less than what they want he said are they prepared to settle 
for some kind of partition of this land 
he said most palestinians are ready for a twostate solution 
but this feeling is like a comet that comes close to the earth 
if one wants to use it one has to grab it while it is there 
he also cited the cumulative affects of 20 years of occupation 
on the new generation noting that half the people of the west bank 
and gaza strip are under 20 years old and 77 percent under 28 
for them he said leadership status is determined by how many 
times you have been in jail how bad was the interrogation and has 
anybody in your family died fighting 
the more yeses to such questions the more of a leader you 
became within your neighborhood or community he added 
as palestinian militancy grew the deterrent power of israels 
army was weakened 
palestinians saw shiite moslem guerrillas drive the israelis out 
of south lebanon in 1985 with a determined guerrilla campaign 
then in late november 1987 a palestinian guerrilla sailed over 
israels welldefended northern border with a hang glider and 
killed six soldiers israeli analysts said the attack encouraged 
palestinians to challenge the army in the occupied territories 
</TEXT>
