<TEXT>
a lawsuit seeking to force citibank to 
obey iowa consumer credit laws potentially could affect other 
companies that like citibank offer credit cards in iowa but base 
their card operations elsewhere the states attorney general says 
attorney general tom miller filed a federal lawsuit monday 
seeking to sto citibank the nations biggest credit card issuer 
from applying the less stringent credit laws of south dakota where 
its credit card operation is based to other states 
the suit contended that although the courts consistently have 
allowed credit card issuers to use the laws of their home state in 
setting interest rates wherever they operate that power should not 
apply to other consumer credit issues 
we are challenging the assumption that they can export the 
laws of states which have few consumer protections into states like 
iowa that have stronger protections for their citizens miller 
said at a news conference announcing the suit 
the suit could affect every bank that has a national credit 
card operation he said 
miller said other states had indicated interest in joining the 
action 
citibanks sioux falls sd office referred reporters calls to 
its new york headquarters spokesman bill mcquire in new york said 
that while the company had not seen the suit it did comply with 
federal law 
citibank is the banking subsidiary of the new yorkbased 
citicorp the nations largest bank holding company it is accused 
of collecting late charges and other fees that are allowed under 
south dakota law but are banned in iowa 
the company has issued about 15 million credit cards nationwide 
but insists that south dakotas consumer laws govern its cards 
wherever they are issued there are 36000 citibank mastercard and 
visa cards issued in iowa 
miller said although iowa has deregulated credit card interest 
rates it also has banned late payment fees and insufficient funds 
check charges iowa also requires companies give three months 
notice before changing the terms of a credit card contract 
the banks argue that iowa law doesnt apply in this 
situation miller said we say our state law does protect 
iowans 
miller also said the south dakota law gave citibank a 
competitive advantage over iowabased issuers who had to follow 
their states stricter credit rules 
millers suit seeks a ban on collection of the late payment 
fees plus unspecified civil penalties and a refund of any payments 
which have been collected 
the state targeted citibank for the suit because it is the 
biggest card issuer although other companies may be sued as well 
miller said the state failed to reach an outofcourt settlement 
over the issue with citibank he said 
the nations top 10 credit card companies have about 64 million 
cards outstanding representing accounts of more than 32 billion 
