<TEXT>
a change in the structure of japans economy 
contributed to the first decline in japans fiscalyear trade 
surplus in eight years government and private analysts said 
tuesday 
the finance ministry announced monday that japans overall trade 
surplus dropped 153 percent in the fiscal year ended march 31 to 
76 billion from 897 billion in the previous fiscal year 
it was the first decline since 1979 when japans oil import 
bill soared because of the second oil crisis 
japans trade surplus with the united states posted its first 
annual decline since 1982 dropping 22 percent to 509 billion 
from a record 52 billion the year before 
a shift toward the direction of a decline in trade surplus is 
taking place at a steady pace said nobuo murakami deputy 
director of the finance ministrys export division 
the yens rapid appreciation against the dollar the past two 
years and the government policy to promote domestic demand were 
major factors in the decline in the surplus murakami said 
the yen has roughly doubled in value against the dollar since 
its most recent low in february 1985 in september 1985 monetary 
authorities from seven major industrialized countries agreed to 
drive down the dollars value to help reduce the huge us trade 
deficit 
a higher yen makes japanese exports more expensive abroad and 
less competitive while imported products are cheaper in japan 
japan sent 358 percent of its exports to the united states in 
fiscal year 1987 down from 38 percent the previous year its 
exports to the european economic community increased to 167 
percent from 154 percent and to southeast asian countries to 237 
percent from 206 percent 
it is clear that some major japanese products including 
automobiles are losing their competiveness on the us market 
though personal computers and other office equipment remain in high 
demand said taku hiramatsu assistant manager of the research 
department of bank of tokyo 
hiramatsu said japans auto exports to the united states which 
accounted for about 30 percent of the nations total exports to the 
united states will be getting further squeezed in the future 
because several japanese automakers will be making car in the 
united states in 1990s 
japanese automakers have fallen short of the governmentset 
export quota of 23 million passenger cars during the year the 
first such shortfall since japan began limting its auto exports to 
the us market in 1981 local news reports said tuesday 
an official of the japan automobile manufacturers association 
said the figures for japans car exports to the united states would 
be announced late this month and the volume would be far below 
the 23 million vehicles sent to america the previous year 
the official who spoke on condition of anonymity blamed the 
shortfall on the higher yen and the slowerthanexpected increase 
in the us car market 
japanese car makers have raised their export prices to the 
united states by more than 20 percent on the average over the past 
two years to make up for losses stemming from the dollars 
depreciation 
more significant results in the reduction of japans trade 
surplus with the united states will surely come in years to come 
murakami said its just two years since the yens appreciation 
began 
