in the last five years when you could hardly get in the door of a 
presentation 
graduate business students participating in a recent conference 
at northwestern said that consulting positions which offer 
starting salaries ranging from 50000 to 100000 are a lot more 
attractive than investment banking careers now because of the 
employment uncertainty raised by the crash 
a good part of my class had pegged hopes on wall street 
said mark sheridan a 28yearold cornell university business 
student at the conference you see a lot of chameleons out there 
suddenly theyre all into consulting 
several schools have projected sharp reductions in the number of 
students who will go into investment banking this year at kellogg 
for example only about 12 percent will accept wall street offers 
down from 17 percent last year columbia university expects about 
15 percent down from 28 percent and pennsylvanias wharton school 
expects about 15 percent down from 25 percent 
wall street firms themselves have been curtailing campus 
recruitment drives this year partly because they are undergoing 
their own postcrash retrenchment but many have found the pool of 
mba talent has shrunk 
this year weve had more people turn down jobs than in the 
past five years said james p gorter a goldman sachs partner 
who spoke at the northwestern conference 
roy cohen manager of professional recruiting at merrill lynch 
capital markets said although his firm hunted for fewer mbas this 
year student interest was down on campus i have to be very 
direct with you about that 
although merrill lynch had no trouble filling positions cohen 
said with the downturn in the market students were starting to 
think about less riskoriented careers 
the shift has been welcomed by major consulting and accounting 
firms which are enjoying strong growth and seeking thousands of 
additional mba graduates at arthur andersen amp co for example 
recruiters expect to hire 8000 new employees this year said 
lawrence a weinbach a managing partner 
john n fox jr a touche ross partner with recruiting 
responsibilities said he has noticed much stronger interest from 
leading schools 
at harvard we saw 230 people more than weve ever seen 
before fox said previously weve seen 150 160 
fox said at least some of those additional applicants had been 
pursuing a wall street career prior to october 
i think those always interested in investment banking are 
still interviewing fox said others have been sobered by 
whats happened 
