<TEXT>
harvard university was granted a patent for a 
genetically altered mouse today the first time a us patent has 
been issued for an animal 
the laboratory mice were altered to make them more susceptible 
to cancer and have been in use in experiments at harvard since 
1984 said university spokeswoman lilliam blacker 
patent commissioner donald j quigg said using the animal will 
simplify cancer research and make it easier to test both 
cancercausing substances and chemicals that fight cancer 
the action drew fire from jeremy rifkin who heads a coalition 
of groups opposed to genetic engineering 
he termed the action a usurpation of power by the patent office 
noting that there have been discussions in congress of imposing a 
moratorium on such patents until ethical questions can be worked 
out 
quigg however said that the patent application which was 
filed in 1984 met the legal criteria for a patent and so one was 
issued ethical questions he said need to be settled in congress 
and the medical laboratories not the patent office 
while this was the first patent on an animal plants and forms 
of bacteria have been patented previously 
the supreme court in 1980 ruled that manmade life organisms 
could be patented but the harvard patent is the first to protect a 
genetic change in a higher life form 
the patent was issued to harvard university with the inventors 
listed as philip leder and timothy a stewart 
quigg said his office has 21 other applications for animal 
patents pending details could not be disclosed however he said 
he said that virtually any changed animal could be patented 
except humans 
patents allow the inventor the exclusive right to use a product 
for 17 years although in practice the patent holder usually 
licenses use of the product for a fee 
this opens the floodgates for a whole range of patents from 
fish to house pets said jack doyle of the environmental policy 
institute which supports a moratorium on animal patents 
but geoffrey karny a washington patent attorney said the 
action was not a radical departure from existing policy 
granting a patent on animals is an entirely logical 
application of existing patent law principles and in many respects 
is nothing different from what society has been doing with regard 
to the commercial ownership of animals for thousands of years 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

